place.desc: St Vincent's Well, now known as St Vincent's Spring, is located about two miles from Bristol city centre on the north side of the river Avon in Clifton. The hot spring water flows from St Vincent's rocks and drinking it was seen to be medically restorative.

place.placeName: St Mary on the Hill, Chester, Cheshire

place.desc: St Mungo’s Well was a popular cold water spring and bath at Copgrove, near Ripon, Yorkshire. It now seems to be covered by a paved area in front of Well House Farm (private land).

Hipswell Hall was Alice Wandesford’s jointure property. It is a 15th-century manor house, built for the Fulthorpe family, whose coat of arms is carved on the bay window to the right. The estate passed to the Wandesfords of Kirklington and over the front door is a plaque dated 1596 with the initials of George Wandesford.

St Oswald, King and Martyr, Oswaldkirk, Yorkshire

place.desc: East Newton Hall was the Thornton family home. William and Alice Thornton have it built anew after their marriage. They move here in 1662 and Robert Thornton was born here. It, together with Laistrop, was part of Alice Thornton’s jointure and she died here in 1707.

St Martin's Lane, Westminster, was first built up in 1610 by Robert Cecil and given its current name in 1618, and by the 1630s had rapidly become one of the most populated areas of London. It ran from St Martin-in-the-Fields church at its south end to Long Acre at its north, and made for a convenient location for royal servants MPs to reside in close proximity to Westminster.
Neston Water, Cheshire, was a port on the Dee Estuary at Neston, Cheshire. A major shipping route to Ireland in the seventeenth century, it silted up and is no longer in use.
